{
  "text": "There has been little written in the emergency medicine literature regarding the use of voice recognition software. In 1989, Spacone analyzed a software program for voicecontrolled text creation that was used on a microcomputer in the emergency medical department of a large hospital. [CITATION_1] It was found that automated speech recognition (ASR) permitted doctors to produce their reports faster and more accurately than handwriting or dictation to tape. In addition, ASR reporting was found to be less expensive than dictation to tape. Other advantages with voice recognition included the ability to create computer-stored patient files that could be used for statistical purposes. Spacone found a few minor drawbacks, including the need for a procedure for training the system to recognize the user's voice.",
